			<h4>Week 13</h4>
			<p><b>Baby : </b>Your cutr fetus has grown to three inches long now head will be only one-fourth the size of her body, balance with the rest of the bod and baby’s face now more clear and eyes have arrived, they’re not open. His eyelids are fused shut to protect.The brain continues to develop, its structure becoming more complex by the day. </p>
			<p>The heart beats at 140–170 beats per minute, pumping about 20 liters (almost 5 gallons) of blood every 24 hours. More and more blood vessels appear, supplying blood to every organ and every tissue in the body.</p>
			<p>The intestines now move out of their space umbilical cord  to their permanent home in baby’s belly. It starts nourishing tiny tummy and the other systems and organs. Baby’s lifeline — the placenta — is expanding. It weighs just an ounce now, </p>
			<p>There are plenty of other changes happening this week as well like</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Fingernails and downy hair on the body  *Baby’s bones continue to harden</li>
				<li>Those genitals begin to take on their gender characteristics.</li>
				<li>The muscles of the chest wall are starting to develop, and start little breathing movements. </li>
				<li>First words start now with the formation of vocal cords.</li>
			</ul>

			<p><b>Mom : </b>Now that you're 13 weeks pregnant and just a week away from the second trimester, you should be feeling pretty good soon. </p>
			<p>But if you're not feeling better yet, don't worry. While most early pregnancy symptoms will probably be behind you soon, some women find that nausea and fatigue linger into the fourth and even fifth months. </p>
			<p>And unfortunately for some women, those and other usual first trimester suspects — such as bloating, constipation, headaches and breast tenderness — can continue to some extent throughout pregnancy. </p>
			<p>Vaginal discharge Of course, even though the second trimester is known as the trimester of smooth sailing, it doesn't mean you'll be symptom-free in the near future — far from it.</p>
			<p>you might have noticed recently is an increase in your vaginal discharge. Known as leukorrhea (try getting that right in a spelling bee), this perfectly normal discharge is thin and milky in color, or mild-smelling or sometimes even odorless. Plus, it'll probably increase as your pregnancy progresses. </p>
			<p>Leukorrhea is caused by the stepped-up production of estrogen as well as the increased blood flow to the pelvic area. Its purpose is noble: to protect the birth canal from infection and maintain a healthy balance of bacteria in the vagina. Unfortunately, in achieving its lofty goal, leukorrhea can make a mess of your underwear. </p>
			<p>If it makes you more comfortable, use a panty liner, never a tampon, to stay dry. But never douche while you're pregnant, which can upset the normal balance of microorganisms, lead to vaginal infections and even force air into the vagina during pregnancy, which can be dangerous. </p>
			<p>Sex during pregnancy With all the extra discharge down there plus your burgeoning belly, you may be wondering whether your feelings about jumping into bed are normal. Try to go with the flow: When it comes to pregnancy sex, anything goes. </p>
			<p>You may not be in the mood at all or you may be up for sex a lot more than usual. All of it is normal and likely to continue fluctuating as your pregnancy progresses</p>

			<p><b>Genetic screening and structural anomaly</b></p>
			<p>In some cases, the first-trimester screening finds a chance of defects in the fetus’s development or potential genetic anomalies. In that case, done extra testing will be advised to confirm or deny those findings. </p>
			<p>Previously, if it was suspected that the baby had chances of chromosomal anomalies, such as Down syndrome, an invasive fetal DNA test was offered. Most often, it would be amniocentesis, where a small amount of amniotic fluid is extracted for testing. Amniocentesis is considered the safest and most accurate of the invasive methods, but unfortunately this method still carries potential risk for the fetus mother have fear. The risk of pregnancy loss after invasive testing ranges from 0.5% to 2%. Another drawback of amniocentesis is that it can only be done after 16 weeks, and it takes a week or two to get results. Such a long waiting period (especially if a predisposition for genetic anomalies was discovered in the first screening) can trigger a lot of anxiety for the mother. </p>
			<p>Thank god, medical research is always ongoing, and now mothers have the option to take a non-invasive prenatal test (NIPT), such as the Panorama test, before subjecting themselves to an invasive procedure. These tests use a blood sample from the mother, from which they extract the baby’s DNA. DNA tests are highly accurate (up to 99% for some conditions) in detecting anomalies in the baby’s development. If the analysis shows less than 1% risk of defects, your baby will likely be just fine. If the risk is higher, it’s worth undergoing an invasive diagnostic test. Notably, NIPT can be done after 9 weeks, and the results come back in a few days.When is it worth taking a Panorama test or other NIPT? Definitely if the results of the first-trimester screening come back showing higher risk, and if there were chromosomal anomalies present in past pregnancies.</p>
			<p>Such testing is also worth considering if the mother is over 35 or the father is over 45. </p>
			<p>DNA tests are completely safe and don’t require any special preparation by the mother. It’s little bit costly so not advisable to all pregnant women. But when it comes to their baby’s future health and the mother’s peace of mind during pregnancy, many parents end up finding the investment worthy</p>

