			<h4>Week 14</h4>
			<p><b>Baby : </b>The baby’s face looks more and more normal. The bridge of the nose is now visible, and small cheeks have appeared. The eyes have moved from the sides of the head to their habitual place. Eyelashes and eyebrows have started to grow, and the optical nerves and eyeballs have formed. The baby can now react to light.</p>
			<p>The external ears are present on the sides of the head. They aren’t fully formed yet, but the baby can already hear well. It can distinguish mom’s pulse from external sounds, and can remember and discern mom’s voice, making this a great time to talk to the baby or turn on some music. Baby’s emotions are expressed through arm and leg movements and facial expressions. The muscles of the face are already formed and functional, allowing the baby to show displeasure, joy, and fear.</p>
			<p>The baby’s skin is thin and red, with lots of blood vessels throughout. It has begun to sprout a thin, downy layer of hair called lanugo. The lanugo will be thickest by 28 weeks, and by delivery it will have fallen out for most babies, although sometimes individual hairs will stay on for 1–2 weeks after delivery and fall out later. Lanugo’s main function is to protect the baby. It catches a waxy substance the fetus produces, called vernix caseosa, forming a dense layer. This lubricant helps the baby come down the birth canal as smoothly as possible during labor.</p>
			<p>The baby is busy swimming in the amniotic sac, working its muscles. It bends its arms and legs, turns its head, and makes faces. By swallowing and spitting out amniotic fluid, it learns to breathe in and out.</p>
			<p>Sweat and saliva glands are being formed, and by the end of week 14 they’re ready to go. In girls, the ovaries begin to descend into the pelvis. In boys, the prostate appears.</p>

			<p><b>Mom : </b>Now you entered the best time to enjoy your pregnancy. Quite safe period for physical exertion. Your body is now used to its new hormonal state, and the morning sickness most gone. You are more likely to have emotional stable, and are more energetic, less lazy. You can enjoy  to your usual routines. This is the best time during pregnancy to engage in permitted forms of exercise, travel, take long walks, attend cultural events, and gradually get everything ready for the baby’s arrival. </p>
			<p>Your body continues to change. Your breasts are not as sensitive and tender as before. Your belly continues to grow: it may not  and people around you still might not notice don't worry if your 1st pregnancy and your abdominal muscles tone good. When  you place your Palm on Lower belly, you may feel for the top edge of the uterus, which is currently 11–13 cm (4.5–5 in) above the pubic bone. This measurement, known as the fundal height, is routinely taken by (before ultrasound era) doctors to track the fetus’s growth. </p>
			<p>In the beginning of  pregnancy, your weight gain should be about 1–3 kg (2–6 lbs), which includes incrased volumes of blood and lymphatic fluid, mom’s subcutaneous fat, amniotic fluid, and, of course, the baby itself. Now morning sickness is gone, it’s important to get a nutritious, balanced diet, which will provide you with the vitamins and minerals you need, and also very critical to keep your digestive system running smoothly with plenty of fluids, great leafy vegetables and high fibre diet. </p>
			<p>Now your face become typically in pregnancy, as your nose and lips increase in size and your cheeks round out. Thee are Patches of pigment may temporarily appear on your face; this is known as the “mask of pregnancy” or chloasma. These are usually symmetrical, yellowish-grey dark patches with a clear edge, and they gradually fade away after the birth.</p>

			<p><b>Useful tips</b></p>
			<p>Most pregnant women have many questions regarding travel during pregnancy. As long as there are no identified pregnancy complications or concerns with your pregnancy, it is generally safe to travel at all times during your pregnancy. The ideal time to travel during pregnancy is during the second trimester.</p>
			<p>At this stage Iron and Calcium Important During Pregnancy </p>
			<p>Your body needs iron to make hemoglobin — that's the substance in your red blood cells that helps carry oxygen to your organs and tissues. When you're pregnant, your body produces more blood to supply oxygen to your baby, which is why you'll need to double your iron intake. If you don't get enough iron, or you're already low on iron, you could develop iron deficiency anemia, which will not only make you feel more tired in pregnancy, but also, in severe cases, can increase the risk of premature birth, low birth weight, and postpartum depression.</p>
			<p>Getting enough calcium helps keep your teeth and bones healthy, and helps your baby develop strong teeth and bones, too. What's more, calcium keeps your circulatory, nervous, and muscular systems running normally. </p>
			<p>So start iron and calcium supplements as per your doctor's advice if you have still not started. </p>
			<p>'If you have allergies or side effects of this medication contact your doctor.</p>
			<p>If you have thalassemia minor or sickle cell minor you may not required iton supplementation.</p>
