			<h4>Week 15</h4>
			<p><b>Baby</b></p>
			<p><b>Movements : </b>By 15 weeks, your baby can make whole-body movements, move their arms and legs, stretch, and make breathing motions.</p>
			<p><b>Ears : </b>The outer part of your baby’s ears is growing and steadily becoming more recognizable. Meanwhile, the inner ear continues to develop. While the baby can't quite hear just yet, it will happen soon.4</p>
			<p><b>Skin : </b>Your baby’s skin is still very thin and translucent, allowing a clear view of the blood vessels and skeleton.</p>
			<p>The layer of downy hair known as lanugo covers the fetus’s back and shoulders, and part of the face. A little later, the skin will become covered in vernix caseosa, a cheese-like waxy substance that helps the baby easily slip out into the outside world during labor. Lanugo not only helps keep this wax in place, but also keeps the baby warm until it can grow subcutaneous fat.</p>
			<p><b>Bones : </b>Bones continue to ossify or harden. Some bones in the skull, spine, and shoulders, along with the collar bone and long bones, have already begun the process. The bones of the hands and feet are also hardening during this week.</p>
			<p><b>Brain : </b> the fetus measures about 10 cm (4 in). It’s a shape like a newborn, but disproportionately big head. Inside this head, the cerebral cortex is starting to form, which takes about a month. The brain’s hemispheres keep becoming more complex, their folds deepening. </p>
			<p>The eyebrows and hair continue to grow and the pigment that will determine hair color is already being produced.</p>
			<p>The baby’s vocal cords are already fully formed and ready to go. If it weren’t for the surrounding liquid, it would let the world know it was there! For now it stays swimming in its dark, warm, and cozy little world, where life outside is just distant noise. If you shine a bright light at mom’s belly, the baby’s heart will beat quicker and it will get agitated, scrunch up its face, and try to hide from the light.</p>

			<p><b>Mom : </b>Now every week you gain a bit of weight as baby grows faster. The average weekly gain is 300-500 grams (about a pound), and over the course of pregnancy you will gain about 8–15 kg (17–33 lbs), depending on your particular body type. The increased weight can cause back pain, because your muscles just aren’t used to this kind of load. So it’s helpful to train your back  through simple exercises, prenatal yoga or gymnastics, or swimming. </p>
			<p>The uterus grows and keeps rising, which can cause heartburn or upset stomach. It’s best to eat smaller meals more frequently, to keep from overloading your digestive system. </p>
			<p>It’s best to keep your skin protected against the sun during this time, especially if it’s prone to developing brown patches. When going out for a walk, don a wide-brimmed hat and apply sunscreen. </p>
			<p>At the start of the second trimester you may find yourself with a stuffed nose. This is not an early cold symptom: high hormone levels increase blood flow to mucous membranes, your sinuses swell, and it becomes harder to breathe. There are bleeding gums also common among pregnant women.</p>
			<p><b>Tips : </b></p>
			<p><b>STRETCH MARK : </b>Some moms-to-be wear them proudly as a "red badge of motherhood." Others don’t want to talk about them. They're pregnancy stretch marks, and though your baby's not even born yet, she's already leaving her mark on you!  </p>

			<p><b>What trimester do pregnant women develop stretch marks? </b></p>
			<p> You’ll most likely start to notice stretch marks on your stomach (and elsewhere) around the end of the second trimester into the beginning of the third trimester, when you’re between 6 and 7 months pregnant. That said, they do sometimes appear sooner.  </p>
			<p> Up to 90 percent of all expecting women get these pink, red, brown or sometimes purplish streaks. You'll most likely notice them across your belly, butt, thighs, hips or breasts. </p>

			<p><b>What causes stretch marks during pregnancy? </b></p>
			<p>Stretch marks are actually tiny tears in the supporting layers of tissue under your skin as it's pulled tight during pregnancy.  </p>
			<p>Whether or not you get stretch marks has a lot to do with the elasticity of your skin. You can mostly thank genetics: If your mother had stretch marks, chances are greater that you probably will too. Lifestyle habits, including eating well and exercising regularly, also promote skin health and elasticity. </p>
			<p><b>Moisturize and massage : </b>Massaging a stretch mark oil or cream on your belly, hips and thighs certainly won't hurt. Some research suggests that formulations with the herb centella or hyaluronic acid (which is already present in the skin) may help prevent stretch marks, but the evidence is far from definitive.  </p>
			<p>No high-quality research proves that cocoa butter, olive oil, almond oil, vitamin E or coconut oil are effective at preventing stretch marks. But some studies have shown that these and other anti-inflammatory and antioxidant plant oils keep skin hydrated and promote wound healing and skin barrier repair.  </p>
			<p>If nothing else, moisturizing daily will help with the dry, itchy skin associated with pregnancy. </p>
			<p> Be sure to use moisturizer early on in your pregnancy, and massage it in gently to maximize effectiveness. Some researchers think it’s the massaging action and not the actual ingredients that may make stretch mark creams effective. </p>
			<p>Keep using the cream or gel of your choice throughout your pregnancy, since any benefits from these products will likely take weeks to have an effect. </p>
			<p><b>Nourish your skin from the inside : </b>Keep taking your prenatal vitamin, which helps ensure you’re getting enough of a variety of nutrients that support both your baby’s development and your skin health. </p>
			<p>Eating plenty of vitamin C-rich foods like peppers, citrus and strawberries may also make your skin less subject to stretch marks. Vitamin C promotes collagen and tissue production, which helps keep skin strong and elastic.  </p>
			<p>While it’s far from proven to work, getting enough vitamin D in your diet may also help with stretch marks, and it certainly can’t hurt. Load up on fatty fish, fortified dairy or dairy substitutes, and eggs, all of which are chock full of vitamin D, plus other pregnancy-friendly vitamins and nutrients (like omega-3 fatty acids and choline). </p>
			<p><b>Keep your weight gain slow and steady : </b>Since rapid weight gain is one of the culprits behind stretch marks, slowly and steadily putting on pounds during pregnancy is one of the most effective ways to help prevent them. It can be easy to overdo it if you’re eating for two. As much as possible, try to follow the general recommendations for caloric intake during pregnancy, which also helps guarantee an overall healthier pregnancy for you and your .</p>
			<p><b>Can I prevent stretch marks? </b></p>
			<p> Unfortunately, there’s no proven way to prevent stretch marks during pregnancy. Try to think of them as modern art for your baby bump, and save your hard-earned cash for a post-delivery treat instead of spending a ton of money on unproven therapies. </p>
			<p><b>Other Skin Changes During Pregnancy : </b>Skin Darkening and Discoloration During Pregnancy</p>
			<p>It’s best to keep your skin protected against the sun during this time, especially if it’s prone to developing brown patches. When going out for a walk, don a wide-brimmed hat and apply sunscreen.</p>
